<div id="subtree-container" class="subtree-container"><div class="aea2d7dde423afa7ad9351a0886150a8-scss b51b00c1669ad99a1c607cd1e77c2824-scss" style="inset: 312px 269px 0px 0px; justify-content: flex-end;"><div class="afeebf1df237d4103108ba40799802d6-scss"><div class="c13443431e58facf06f9d12490b92a82-scss" style="width: 90vw; max-width: 8.5in;"><div class="_0df5ec6b9902d7d22ccfa3ebb4f35211-scss">ISO 19650 Hierarchy of Information Requirements</div><div class="e5e059a27f4c194020f0d961a3cb5989-scss" dir="auto"><div class="fr-view"><p class="p1" data-pasted="true">To define our AIR clearly, it helps to understand how it fits into the <span class="s1"><strong>overall information management process</strong></span> under the ISO 19650 framework.</p>
<p class="p1">ISO 19650 provides a structured way to define and manage information throughout the lifecycle of a built asset - from initial planning to operation. One of the core ideas is that <span class="s1"><strong>not all information is created equal,</strong></span> different people need different types of information at different times, and for different purposes.</p>
<p class="p1">Here’s how the hierarchy is defined:</p>
<p><img src="https://files.plannerly.com/projects/89b0b4c8-ddfb-4818-adb4-b719d6b49723/plan-content/1762744652267_4f050849-6bab-44a7-96e0-a0a2a1e0df20.png?Expires=1768815902&amp;Signature=h1rSkQ6m8LxfvVRDaAAaUCl9FXzp0A4JhFLEKoSKoCYsM4ATIbuJDh1AIF2c3oilwzFZU82uP4UTtEyMtBalMoZUhV8RepEk0MgAK4zntQwrXLKC8z1EohB3Ji9kFjTKT34o8pszugZO9Si-X-x6QY-HFBX5EHYCWzAqFzbFQ5UkozwEjGlpOmGgmWPlsbdRW2hBeWzYBcSH3k-Fay8HsgYWuJCiw4pIEB13pA2mfFKzXlIdiJiWcq0Vyoa~fJmXATSB4uP0acloxVmaxF~oqXmcgTxubBrS-NTN3DufwgtdiX30R6pwErqs~MDzdtPqNBWjo89nFYzgkwggEkEbkg__&amp;Key-Pair-Id=APKAJRIVA6WNZT4BZJPQ" style="width: 1075px;" class="fr-fic fr-dib"></p>
<h3><strong>Why This Matters</strong></h3>
<p class="p3">If we start by clearly defining our AIR, we can:</p>
<ul>
<li><p class="p1">Set meaningful expectations with our delivery team</p></li>
<li><p class="p1">Avoid confusion about what’s “nice to have” vs “must have”</p></li>
<li><p class="p1"><span class="s1">Make sure our </span><strong>Scope module entries</strong><span class="s1"> reflect </span><strong>real operational value</strong></p></li>
</ul></div></div></div></div></div></div>